to do so. He also engages the political and moral issues raised by the idea of a multicultural art history. Focusing on a consideration of intersecting artistic traditions, Carrier negotiates the way meaning and understanding shift or are altered when a visual object from one culture, for example, is inserted into the visual tradition of another culture. A World Art History and Its Objects proposes the use of temporal narrative as a way to begin to understand a multicultural art history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aArtxHistoriographyxMethodology. 0aArtxHistoriographyxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPolitics and culture. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271036069?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271036069423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271036069/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK